00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:44.590
JESSICA: So what
did Dr. Dolhun do?

00:01:44.590 --> 00:01:47.770
Well, he added three
solutions to the flask.

00:01:47.770 --> 00:01:52.620
Solution 1 was glucose in water.

00:01:52.620 --> 00:01:55.770
Solution 2 was a mixture of
silver nitrate and ammonium

00:01:55.770 --> 00:01:57.700
nitrate.

00:01:57.700 --> 00:02:01.660
And Solution 3 was sodium
hydroxide, which is a base.

00:02:01.660 --> 00:02:05.070
So let's focus on the
second two solutions first.

00:02:05.070 --> 00:02:08.740
When you mix solutions 2
and 3, two things happen.

00:02:08.740 --> 00:02:15.000
First, you form Ag2O, which
is insoluble in water.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.370
So it precipitates
out as a brown solid.

00:02:21.010 --> 00:02:25.380
The sodium hydroxide reacts
with ammonium and H4 plus

00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:27.140
to produce ammonia, NH3.

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:31.930
This dissolves the precipitate.

00:02:31.930 --> 00:02:39.760
And you end up with Ag(NH3)2,
which all has a positive

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:41.330
charge.

00:02:41.330 --> 00:02:44.500
This is soluble in water, and
it's called Tollens Reagent.

00:02:47.890 --> 00:02:50.510
Now, the positive charge
is borne by the silver.

00:02:50.510 --> 00:02:55.000
So what we have in solution
is essentially silver ions.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:59.710
Now looking at Solution 1,
glucose looks like this.

00:03:03.570 --> 00:03:07.680
We don't really care about this
whole part of the molecule.

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:10.740
So we're going to call
it R for "the rest."

00:03:13.890 --> 00:03:15.850
So glucose is basically this.

00:03:18.910 --> 00:03:20.770
And this part of
the glucose is going

00:03:20.770 --> 00:03:23.830
to start reacting
with the silver ions.

00:03:23.830 --> 00:03:26.497
Let's watch what happens.

